  "body": " Linear Models   Linear equations are frequently used to construct simple models of the interaction between two quantities. We will illustrate this with a few examples below. Think about the appropriate choice of linear form in each example.  Standard Form:  Point-Slope Form:  Slope-Intercept Form:       A rectangular fence is to be constructed from a fixed budget of 1000 dollars. Two parallel sides of the fence are constructed from a material costing 4 dollars per foot, while the remaining sides are constructed from a material costing 3 dollars per foot. Express these constraints as a linear equation.    Let denote the length of the sides costing 4 dollars per foot and let denote the length of the sides costing 3 dollars per foot. Then the cost of the fence is . The fixed budget imposes the linear constraint      A gasoline-powered generator has a fuel tank capacity of gallons and consumes fuel at a rate gallons per hour. Find a linear model for the fuel consumption over time. How long can the generator run on a full tank?    Let be the amount of fuel in the tank after running for hours. Then initially, , when , determining the -intercept. The rate of decrease of fuel provides the slope . So, The tank will be empty when which we solve to find hours.     A company earns a revenue of from selling units of their product. They earn from selling units. Find a linear relationship modeling the revenue in terms of number of units sold.   Let denote the revenue and denote the number of units sold. The data provided allows us to find the rate at which revenue changes as we increase the number of units sold: So the slope of our line is dollars per unit. We can now use point-slope form along with either data point to find a linear equation     "
