  "number": "7.2",
  "title": "Graphing Functions",
  "body": " Graphing Functions  The graph of a function is a visual representation of the relationship between the inputs and corresponding output of a function. We typically plot inputs on the horizontal -axis and the corresponding output on the vertical -axis. Each input\/output pair determines a point on the graph .   Suppose is a real-valued function of a real variable. The graph of is the graph of the equation . The graph consists of all points , with in the domain of .   The graph of the squaring function  Let , the squaring function. The graph of is the graph of the equation . It consists of all points , where is any real number. For instance, so that is a point on the graph. Similarly, so that is also point on the graph. The resulting curve is called a parabola .   Visualize the domain along the horizontal axis and the range along the vertical axis. Observe how I have labeled the curve with its equation . This is a practice should adhere to as well when graphing.    A function given by its graph  A function may be described entirely by its graph. For example, the odd looking graph below determines a function which I will call . We can use the graph to evaluate . For instance, , or at least appears to be so if the graph truly includes the point . Similarly, , which I'm definitely estimating here. This determines the -intercept of the graph. A value of where is called a (real) zero of and corresponds to an -intercept of the graph. It appears that this function has zeros at and at .  The behavior of the graph at is subtle. There is clearly a point plotted at so that . The hole at is used to emphasize that no point is plotted here. In fact, if there was not a hole here as in then this would not be a the graph of a function as the value of is associated to two different -coordinates. This violates the uniqueness requirement in   The domain of can be visualized along the horizontal -axis; the range along the vertical -axis.    In this case, the domain of is the interval . We exclude because no point is plotted at . The range of is the interval , excluding both and .  A vertical line drawn to the left or the right of the circle does not intersect the graph at all. This is fine, as these correspond to values of not in the domain of these functions.    When is a function and we write , we are saying that is a function of , that is, the value of is explicitly determined by the value of . Graphically, this means a vertical line corresponding to a value of in the domain of the function should intersect the graph once.   Vertical Line Test  Suppose is a real-valued function of the variable . Then any vertical line will intersect the graph of at most once. In this case, the graph is said to pass the vertical line test .  On the other hand, if there is a vertical line which intersects a graph more than once, then this is not the graph of a function of . In this case, the graph is said to fail the vertical line test .    A circle is not the graph of any function  Consider the graph of the equation which forms the unit circle of radius 1 centered at the origin. A vertical line drawn between intersects the circle exactly twice. The value of here does not explicitly determine the value of . Thus, is not a function of and the circle is not the graph of any function.  We can make some progress if we solve for using the Square Root Principle : There are really two equations here, and , which correspond to the upper and lower semi-circles. These graphs do pass the vertical line test individually and so are graphs of functions.   How many -intercepts can the graph of a function have? Must it have any -intercepts? How many zeros can the graph of a function have? Must it have any>  "
