  "number": "8.6",
  "title": "Exponential Equations",
  "body": " Exponential Equations  Logarithms are a useful tool for expressing solutions to exponential equations. We'll consider some examples in this section.   Solving an Exponential Equation   Consider the exponential equation . First observe that this equation must have a unique solution. This is because the exponential function is one-to-one. In the figure below it appears that the graph of crosses exactly once somewhere near .   Plot of and .    On the one hand, we can rewrite the equation in logarithmic form to obtain . So that the solution is a logarithm. Unfortunately, your calculator is unlikely to have the ability to estimate base 5 logarithms.  Alternatively, we can express the solution in terms of the natural logarithm. Apply the natural logarithm to both sides to obtain an equivalent equation: Use the power property of logarithms and solve for  Thus, it must be that our base 5 answer is equal to this ratio of natural logarithms: We can now estimate with a calculator by diving the two logs. In exponential form,    The previous example illustrates the following change of base formula. In principle, one only needs the natural logarithm to solve exponential equations.   Change of Base for Logarithms  For ,     Solving an Exponential Equation   Solve     First, isolate the exponential term Now apply the natural logarithm to both sides and use the power property of logarithms which can now be estimated with a calculator      Solving an Exponential Equation   The value in dollars of a car after years since purchase depreciates according to the formula How log will it take before the car is worth a quarter of its original purchase price?    The purchase price is A quarter of this amount is dollars. We want to solve the equation So, Estimating with a calculator, We expect it to take 3.63 years for the car to depreciate to a quarter of its original purchase price.    "
